T1  - Monetary policy under alternative bank market structures
AU  - VanHoose, David D.
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 7
IS  - 3
SP  - 383
EP  - 404
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/09/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(83)90045-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0378426683900456
AB  - The purpose of this paper is to derive and compare the short-run effects of monetary policy under both perfectly and imperfectly competitive banking markets. Within the context of a general equilibrium framework which emphasizes the demands for and supplies of financial assets, it is demonstrated that the structure of banking markets can have a bearing on the appropriate choice of policy targets and instruments. Specifically, the Federal Funds rate is shown to be a potentially ineffective target/instrument for policy under a competitive banking system, although it can be used to produce conventional short-run effects when banking markets are imperfect. In contrast, the level of currency and unborrowed reserves can be utilized as an effective target/instrument under either form of bank market structure.
